'''Ga<U+00EB>l Sebastien Monfils''' ({{IPA-fr|<U+0261>a<U+025B>l m<U+0254><U+0303><U+02C8>fis}}; born 1 September 1986) is a [[France|French]] professional [[tennis]] player. Monfils is a former French No. 1, reaching a career-high singles ranking of World No. 7 and winning 4 singles titles. He was the runner-up at the [[BNP Paribas Masters|Paris Masters]] in [[2009 BNP Paribas Masters <U+2013> Singles|2009]] and [[2010 BNP Paribas Masters <U+2013> Singles|2010]] and a semifinalist at the [[2008 French Open - Men's Singles|2008 French Open]].

== Tennis career==
===Junior===
As a junior Monfils compiled a singles win/loss record of 83-22, reaching the No. 1 junior world combined ranking in February 2004. In 2004 he won the Boys' Singles titles at the [[2004 Australian Open#Boys' Singles|Australian Open]], the [[2004 French Open#Boys' Singles|French Open]] and [[2004 Wimbledon Championships#Boys' Singles|Wimbledon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ATP Player Profile <U+2013> Gael Monfils|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Players/Top-Players/Gael-Monfils.aspx|publisher=ATP}}</ref> He was crowned International Tennis Federation youth world champion.<ref name=connexion/>

<u>Junior Slam results:</u>

Australian Open: '''W''' ([[2004 Australian Open#Boys' Singles|2004]])<br />
French Open: '''W''' ([[2004 French Open#Boys' Singles|2004]])<br />
Wimbledon: '''W''' ([[2004 Wimbledon Championships#Boys' Singles|2004]])<br />
US Open: 3R ([[2003 US Open (tennis)#Boys' Singles|2003]], [[2004 US Open (tennis)#Boys' Singles|2004]])<br />

===2002===
In 2002, Monfils finished 24th at the Dutch Junior Open. In the same year, he won the German Junior Open (defeating Bayer). Monfils ended the year ranked the No. 4 junior in the world. He also represented France in the junior Davis Cup.

===2003===
Monfils got off to a positive start in 2003 and earned his first career ATP point at the France Futures No. 13 by reaching the second round. He also reached the second round at France No. 14, Egypt No. 2, and Spain No. 28. In that year, he played a total of nine Futures events. This included a showing in the doubles final at Spain No. 27. In junior events, he was a semifinalist at Orange Bowl (losing to [[Marcos Baghdatis]]) and USTA International Winter Championships (losing to Sebastian Rieschick). He reached the quarterfinals of the Australian Open juniors tournament (losing to [[Florin Mergea]]) and won the doubles title at the Victorian Junior Championships (with [[Josselin Ouanna]]). He was No. 21 in junior rankings at the end of the year.

===2004===
In 2004, the French teenager finished as the world's no. 1 junior, winning three of four junior Grand Slam events ([[Australian Open]], [[French Open]], [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Record ninth title at SW19 for Woodbridge|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/tennis/record-ninth-title-at-sw19-for-woodbridge-1-537885|publisher=Scotsman|accessdate=9 October 2012|date=5 July 2004}}</ref>  He improved his ATP Entry Ranking by over 700 positions. In October, he made his ATP debut as a wildcard entrant at the [[Moselle Open]] in [[Metz]] and, after winning his first ATP match against [[Xavier Malisse]], reached the quarterfinals in which he lost to countryman [[Richard Gasquet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gasquet garde la main|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/sports/gasquet-garde-la-main-16-10-2004-2005378508.php|publisher=Le Parisien|accessdate=9 October 2012|date=16 Oct 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mathieu wins in straight sets|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/tennis/news/story?id=1902686|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=9 October 2012|date=October 15, 2004}}</ref>   He qualified for the [[2004 BNP Paribas Masters|Paris Masters]] and reached the second round, beating former top-10 player [[Thomas Enqvist]] before falling to World No. 3 [[Lleyton Hewitt]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hewitt blocks Gael force|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Tennis/Hewitt-blocks-Gael-force/2004/11/03/1099362218107.html|publisher=The Age|accessdate=9 October 2012|date=November 4, 2004}}</ref>  He won junior titles at the Australian Open (defeating Ouanna), French Open (defeating Kuznetsov), and [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] (defeating Kasiri). He did not drop a set in Australia and lost one set each at the French Open and Wimbledon. He reached the third round at the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] (losing to Troicki). He also won the LTA International Junior Championship in Roehampton (defeating Murray). He was the runner-up at the Australian Hardcourt Junior Championships (losing to Zverev) and was 31<U+2013>2 in junior events. In April, he reached his first career Futures final at Italy No. 4 (losing to Dlouhy). A week later, he won his first Futures title at Great Britain No. 1 (defeating Bogdanovi<U+0107>). He reached the quarterfinals of the Grenoble Challenger. He went 14<U+2013>6 in Futures and 3<U+2013>5 in Challengers in 2004.

In doubles, Monfils reached the final at France No. 7 (with Ouanna). He reached the semifinals at the Australian Open and the quarterfinals at the French Open (with Ouanna).

===2005===
In 2005, the young Frenchman made one of the biggest moves in the top 50 from the previous season, climbing 200 ranking spots. He finished the year as the no. 3 Frenchman (behind no. 16 [[Richard Gasquet]], no. 26 [[S<U+00E9>bastien Grosjean]]) and captured his first ATP title, while reaching two additional finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=ATP <U+2013> Singles Ranking|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Rankings/Singles.aspx?d=26.12.2005&r=1&c=#|publisher=ATP|accessdate=9 October 2012|date=26 December 2005}}</ref> In the first six months, he won Challenger titles in [[Besan<U+00E7>on]], defeating [[Christophe Rochus]],  and [[Tunis]] (defeating Santoro), and also reached the fourth round at the [[2005 NASDAQ-100 Open|Miami Masters]] (losing to Hrbaty) and a Grand Slam best third round appearance at [[2005 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] (losing to [[Mario An<U+010D>i<U+0107>]]). He compiled a 10<U+2013>14 record in ATP level play and 12<U+2013>1 in Challengers through July.

In the last three months, he went 15<U+2013>8, highlighted by his first ATP clay title at the Idea Prokom Open in Sopot defeating [[Florian Mayer]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monfils wins breakthrough title|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/4129560.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 October 2012|date=7 August 2005}}</ref>  Then he struggled with a 2<U+2013>5 mark before reaching the final in two of the last three indoor tournaments of the season, both in his native country in [[Open de Moselle|Metz]] (losing to Ljubi<U+010D>i<U+0107>) and [[Grand Prix de Tennis de Lyon|Lyon]] (losing to Roddick). He went 11<U+2013>4 in tie-breaks and 1<U+2013>2 vs. top-10 opponents, defeating no. 10 [[Gast<U+00F3>n Gaudio]] in his first match of the season in Doha. He compiled records of 12<U+2013>10 on hard courts, 6<U+2013>7 on clay, 5<U+2013>2 on carpet, and 2<U+2013>3 on grass.

===2006===
In his first tournament of 2006, in [[Doha]], he reached the final, but lost 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>7 to world no. 1 [[Roger Federer]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Federer shows he will still be the force in 2006|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/tennis/federer-primed/2006/01/08/1136655088076.html|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=The Age|date=January 9, 2006}}</ref>  In a surprising event in Las Vegas, there was a tennis paddle tournament held by the Tennis Channel. Monfils was given a wildcard into the doubles event, but became more interested and inquired about getting a singles wildcard into the main draw. However, he received an entry into the qualifying singles (which he won). Monfils competed in the main draw of this [[Paddle tennis]] tournament and surprised everyone when he ousted world no. 1 paddle tennis player [[Scott Freedman]] and eventually went on to win the whole tournament.

Later on in 2006, Monfils reached the semifinals of the Rome [[Tennis Masters Series]], before losing to eventual champion [[Rafael Nadal]]. En route to the semifinals, Monfils defeated former world no. 1 [[Andy Roddick]]. He then entered the [[2006 Hamburg Masters|Hamburg Masters]] event, where he lost in straight sets to fellow teenager [[Andy Murray]] in the first round. After that, he faced Murray once more, this time in the first round of the French Open. After a gruelling five<U+2013>set battle, Monfils emerged victorious. Monfils then proceeded to play the Belgian [[Dick Norman]] in the second round. Once again, the match went to five sets, and Monfils got the better of his formidable opponent. Monfils then faced his toughest opponent yet, the American [[James Blake]]. Blake was the favourite for the win, as he was eighth seed, while Monfils was 25th seed. However, Monfils defeated Blake in another five-set match. Monfils described this run as a marathon. Blake said of Monfils that 'he was the fastest man on the tour'. The fourth round was Monfils' last, as he lost to [[Novak Djokovi<U+0107>]] in straight sets. Monfils said after the match: 'I am disappointed that I didn't take the opportunity, but you can expect me to return next year'. Monfils then left the court to a standing ovation.

As a result of his progress at the French Open, Monfils moved up five positions to reach a career high of no. 23. This also made him the no. 1 player in France, two positions ahead of S<U+00E9>bastien Grosjean.<ref>{{cite web|title=ATP <U+2013> Singles Rankings|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Rankings/Singles.aspx?d=12.06.2006&r=1&c=#|publisher=ATP|accessdate=9 October 2012|date=12 June 2006}}</ref> 

Monfils then entered the [[Stella Artois Championships]], where he won his first-round match against [[J<U+00FC>rgen Melzer]]. He then played the American [[Bobby Reynolds]] and won in straight sets. His third-round encounter was the third time he faced the world no. 4 [[Ivan Ljubi<U+010D>i<U+0107>]]. Though the odds were against his, Monfils triumphed in straight sets, 7<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>5. His quarterfinal draw was with [[James Blake]], whom he had met earlier at the French Open. This time Blake succeeded. After having lost a set, Monfils retired as a result of a back injury. This injury effectively ruled him out of the Nottingham championships the following week.

At the [[2006 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], Monfils suffered a surprising first-round exit when defeated by [[Igor Kunitsyn]]. Monfils won the first set, but ended up losing the next three, 7<U+2013>5, 6<U+2013>7, 3<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6.

===2007===
[[File:Gael force in action.jpg||thumb|280px|Monfils serving against Baghdatis]]
At the [[2007 Australian Open]], Monfils lost to his compatriot [[Richard Gasquet]] in the third round, 0<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>4, 5<U+2013>7, 3<U+2013>6. Monfils had a good run in [[Hypo Group Tennis International|Poertschach]] as a warm-up for the French Open. He lost in the final against [[Juan M<U+00F3>naco]] of Argentina in the fourth final of Montfils' career, 6<U+2013>7, 0<U+2013>6.<ref>{{cite news|title=Argentine Monaco beats Monfils for second title|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/05/26/us-tennis-men-poertschach-idUSL2670688020070526|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=May 26, 2007}}</ref>  He lost in the third round of the French Open to [[David Nalbandian]] in a four-set match. At [[2007 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], Monfils reached the third round without dropping a set, where he lost to [[Nikolay Davydenko]], the sixth seed, in straight sets, 3<U+2013>6, 5<U+2013>7, 3<U+2013>6. Monfils made it to the semifinals of the [[2007 Legg Mason Tennis Classic]], before losing to American [[John Isner]] in a 7<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>7, 6<U+2013>7 match. Monfils withdrew from the [[2007 US Open (tennis)|2007 US Open]] with a hamstring injury. He also was forced to withdraw from the [[2008 Australian Open]] due to the same injury.

===2008===
In the French Open, Monfils reached a semifinal berth for the first time in any Grand Slam, becoming the first Frenchman in the semifinals since 2001. Monfils was defeated by top seed [[Roger Federer]], 2<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>5, 3<U+2013>6, 5<U+2013>7.<ref>{{cite news|title=Broken contact lens ends Monfils' dream|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/06/06/us-tennis-open-monfils-idUSL0664529820080606|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Jun 6, 2008}}</ref>  A shoulder injury forced Monfils to withdraw from the [[2008 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] shortly before he was due to play his first-round match. Monfils was selected to play in the Olympics in Beijing by France, losing to third seed [[Novak Djokovic]] in the quarterfinals, 6<U+2013>4, 1<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6. At the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]], Monfils lost in the fourth round to [[Mardy Fish]] in straight sets, after having defeated former world no. 3 [[David Nalbandian]] again in straight sets, 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>2.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fish wrecks Monfils's 22nd birthday|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/09/02/us-tennis-open-fish-idUSL127046820080902|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Sep 1, 2008}}</ref>  In the [[Thailand Open (tennis)|Thailand Open]], Monfils reached the semifinals, losing to [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]], 0<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6. Monfils lost in the final of the [[BA-CA Tennis Trophy]], 4<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6, to [[Philipp Petzschner]] in the final.

===2009===
Monfils played in [[Qatar ExxonMobil Open|Doha]] as his first tournament and caused an upset in the quarterfinals against Nadal, 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>4.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monfils stuns Nadal with defeat in Qatar|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/01/08/us-tennis-men-qatar-idUSTRE5075AY20090108|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Jan 8, 2009}}</ref>  Monfils lost to finalist [[Andy Roddick]] in three sets, 6<U+2013>7, 6<U+2013>3, 3<U+2013>6, being up a break in the first set 5<U+2013>4 and losing it. In the [[2009 Australian Open|Australian Open]], Monfils lost to fellow Frenchman [[Gilles Simon]] in the fourth round, 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>2, 1<U+2013>6, retiring due to a wrist injury.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sorry Simon sees friend Monfils retire in pain|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/01/26/us-tennis-open-simon-idUSTRE50P0N220090126|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Jan 26, 2009}}</ref>  At the [[2009 Abierto Mexicano Telcel|Abierto Mexicano Telcel]], Monfils lost in the final to [[Nicol<U+00E1>s Almagro]], 4<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6. Monfils competed at the [[Monte Carlo Masters]], losing in the first round to [[Janko Tipsarevi<U+0107>]] with the score, 3<U+2013>6, 1<U+2013>6.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monfils tumbles out of Monte Carlo Masters|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/04/14/us-tennis-men-masters-tuesday-idUSTRE53D2G920090414|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Apr 14, 2009}}</ref> 

His recent knee injury, caused by [[Osgood-Schlatter disease]], resulted in his withdrawal from the [[Rome Masters|Rome]] and the [[Madrid Masters]].<ref>[http://au.sports.yahoo.com/tennis/news/article/-/5513441/monfils-doubtful-french-open/ Monfils Doubtful for French Open, Retrieved 21 April 2009]</ref> However, he competed at the [[French Open|Roland Garros]], and won his first-round match against [[Bobby Reynolds]], 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>1. He then completed another straight-set victory in the second round by overcoming [[Victor Crivoi]], 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>3. In the third round, Monfils beat [[J<U+00FC>rgen Melzer]], 6<U+2013>2, 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>1. Against Melzer, Monfils made one of the most spectacular plays{{Says who|date=February 2011}} of the tournament, hitting a diving lob back to Melzer, sliding to save another point of Melzer and then putting the point away. He then played a much-anticipated fourth-round match against [[Andy Roddick]], who made 28 unforced errors and allowing Monfils to win in straight sets, 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>3. Monfils lost, as in the previous year, to [[Roger Federer]], this time in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Federer silences Monfils to book semis spot|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/03/us-tennis-open-federer-sb-idUSTRE55257720090603|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Jun 3, 2009}}</ref> 

Monfils withdrew from the [[2009 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]] due to a wrist injury. Monfils returned to competition at the [[2009 Rogers Cup|Montreal Masters]]. In his first-round match, he defeated [[Marat Safin]], 6<U+2013>2, 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>2. He lost to qualifier [[Juan Carlos Ferrero]] in his second match, 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>7, ending his Master Series campaign. In the [[2009 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], he lost to world no. 3 [[Rafael Nadal]] in the fourth round in four sets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nadal downs Monfils after sticky start|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/09/09/us-tennis-open-nadal-idUSTRE58818020090909|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Sep 9, 2009}}</ref>  Monfils won the [[Open de Moselle]] held in Metz, France as the top seed. He faced [[Philipp Kohlschreiber]] in the final and won, 7<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>2. Monfils made the quarterfinals at the [[Malaysian Open (tennis)|Malaysian Open]] held in [[Kuala Lumpur]], despite suffering from [[jetlag]], losing 3<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6 to [[Nikolay Davydenko]].

At the [[Japan Open Tennis Championships|Japan Open]], Monfils reached the semifinal stage, losing to eventual champion [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]]. His next tournament was the [[2009 Shanghai ATP Masters 1000|Shanghai Masters]], losing against [[Ivan Ljubi<U+010D>i<U+0107>]] in the third round. He lost the first set 2<U+2013>6, and then was forced to retire with a back injury, when Ljubicic was leading the second set 3<U+2013>0. At the [[2009 BNP Paribas Masters <U+2013> Singles|Paris Masters]], Monfils was defeated the final by [[Novak Djokovic]], 2<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>5, 6<U+2013>7.<ref>{{cite news|title=Djokovic shrugs off Monfils challenge|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/11/15/us-tennis-men-masters-idUSTRE5AE1B220091115|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Nov 15, 2009}}</ref>

===2010===
Monfils began his season at the [[Brisbane International]], where he was seeded third. He lost to defending champion, Czech [[Radek <U+0160>t<U+011B>p<U+00E1>nek]], 2<U+2013>6, 1<U+2013>6, in the semifinals. He withdrew from the [[Medibank International]] in Sydney, Australia, citing a shoulder injury. At the [[2010 Australian Open|Australian Open]], Monfils lost in the round of 32 to [[John Isner]] in four sets, 1<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>7, 6<U+2013>7. Monfils was the first seed at the [[2010 SA Tennis Open|SA Tennis Open]], where he lost in the semifinals to [[Feliciano L<U+00F3>pez]], 6<U+2013>3, 1<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>7.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lopez, Robert reach final in Johannesburg|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/02/06/lopez-robert-reach-final-johannesburg/|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=February 06, 2010}}</ref>  He then played in the [[2010 ABN AMRO World Tennis Tournament|ABN AMRO World Tennis Tournament]] in Rotterdam, where he fell in the quarterfinals to the eventual runner-up, Russian [[Mikhail Youzhny]], 7<U+2013>5, 2<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6. Monfils was the third seed at the [[2010 Open 13]] in Marseille, France where, in the quarterfinals, he lost to [[Julien Benneteau]] in straight sets.

At the [[2010 BNP Paribas Open|BNP Paribas Open]], seeded 12th, after receiving a bye in the first round, Monfils lost to [[Simon Greul]] in three sets. Monfils withdrew from three consecutive Masters 1000 events, the [[2010 Sony Ericsson Open|Sony Ericsson Open]], the [[2010 Monte-Carlo Rolex Masters|Monte-Carlo Masters]], and the [[2010 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Rome Masters]]. He was set to return at the [[2010 Estoril Open|Estoril Open]] and receive a wildcard, but withdrew due to a stomach injury. He finally made his return at the [[2010 Mutua Madrile<U+00F1>a Madrid Open|Madrid Open]] and reach the quarterfinals without losing a set, but there he lost 1<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6, to the third seed [[Rafael Nadal]]. He then played at the [[2010 Open de Nice C<U+00F4>te d'Azur|Open de Nice C<U+00F4>te d'Azur]] in Nice, France, where he lost in the quarterfinals to [[Potito Starace]] 6<U+2013>7, 2<U+2013>6. His next tournament was the [[2010 French Open]], where he had reached the quarterfinals the year before. He was up two sets and a break, before being upset by [[Fabio Fognini]] 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>4, 5<U+2013>7, 4<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>9, in a match over two days.

Starting his grass-court season, Monfils lost in the second round at the [[2010 AEGON Championships|AEGON Championships]] to [[Rainer Sch<U+00FC>ttler]] in three sets 3<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>6, 2<U+2013>6. Playing at [[2010 Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] for the first time since 2007, he won his first match in straight sets against [[Leonardo Mayer]] 6<U+2013>1, 7<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>2, and his second round match in four sets against [[Karol Beck]] 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>7, 6<U+2013>4. He eventually lost to grass-court specialist and former Wimbledon champion [[Lleyton Hewitt]] in straight sets 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>7, 4<U+2013>6. Wimbledon is the only Grand Slam in which Monfils has yet to pass the third round. At the [[2010 MercedesCup| MercedesCup]], he reached his first final of the year by beating [[Daniel Gimeno-Traver]] in three sets 6<U+2013>4, 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>0. He was forced to retire in the final against [[Albert Monta<U+00F1><U+00E9>s]].

At the [[2010 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], he lost to [[Novak Djokovic]] 6<U+2013>7, 1<U+2013>6, 2<U+2013>6, in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monfils blown off court by high winds at U.S. Open|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2010/09/09/us-tennis-open-monfils-wind-idUSTRE68803W20100909|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Sep 8, 2010}}</ref>  It was his first quarterfinals at a major besides the French Open. He is also the first Frenchman to make the US Open quarterfinals since [[Arnaud Cl<U+00E9>ment]] in 2000. Monfils was runner-up at the Rakuten Japan Open, losing to [[Rafael Nadal]] 1<U+2013>6, 5<U+2013>7.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nadal beats Monfils to win Japan Open|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/10/10/nadal-beats-monfils-win-japan-open/|publisher=Fox News / AP|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=October 10, 2010}}</ref>  At the Open de Sud, Monfils won his third tournament, defeating [[Ivan Ljubi<U+010D>i<U+0107>]] 6<U+2013>2, 5<U+2013>7, 6<U+2013>1. Monfils was seeded 12th in the [[BNP Paribas Masters]], where he lost to [[Robin S<U+00F6>derling]] 1<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>7, in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Soderling gears up for O2 with Paris title|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2010/11/14/us-tennis-men-masters-sunday-idUSTRE6AD1QF20101114|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=Nov 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Robin Soderling Defeats Gael Monfils to Win First Masters Tennis Title|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-14/robin-soderling-defeats-gael-monfils-to-win-first-masters-tennis-title.html|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=Nov 14, 2010}}</ref>

===2011===
[[File:Gael Monfils Doha.jpg|thumb|250px|Gael Monfils during the final of the Qatar Exxonmobil Open in Doha.]]
Monfils started 2011 with the [[AAMI Kooyong Classic]], where, in the final, he lost to Australian former world no. 1 [[Lleyton Hewitt]] 5<U+2013>7, 2<U+2013>6.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hewitt wins Kooyong final against Monfils|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/01/15/hewitt-wins-kooyong-final-monfils/|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=January 15, 2011}}</ref>  Monfils was seeded 12th in the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]], where he was defeated in the third round by [[Stanislas Wawrinka]] of Switzerland 6<U+2013>7, 2<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6. Next, Monfils played the [[2011 SAP Open|SAP Open]]. He was able to reach the semifinals, before he had to withdraw with a left wrist injury that had been affecting him since January.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monfils out of SAP Open tennis due to injury|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jUq_-SSdN5qu6cFPG7Zlc5I4paTA?docId=CNG.05f50962e91c5906726818f7488d1bdb.301|publisher=Google / AFP|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=Feb 12, 2011}}</ref> 

In the [[2011 French Open|French Open]], Monfils defeated seventh seed [[David Ferrer]] 6<U+2013>4, 2<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>5, 1<U+2013>6, 8<U+2013>6, to reach the quarterfinals. In the quarterfinals, he lost to [[Roger Federer]] 4<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>7.<ref>{{cite news|title=Federer breezes into Djokovic semi-final|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/05/31/us-tennis-open-federer-idUSTRE74U58A20110531|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=May 31, 2011}}</ref>  Monfils entered [[Wimbledon 2011|Wimbledon]] as the ninth seed.<ref>[http://blogs.montrealgazette.com/2011/06/15/wimbledon-seeds-announced/ 2011 Wimbledon seeds]</ref> In the first round, he defeated [[Matthias Bachinger]] of Germany, 6<U+2013>4, 7<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3. In the second round, he defeated [[Grega Zemlja]] 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>3, 7<U+2013>6. Monfils was defeated in the third round by [[Lukasz Kubot]] of Poland 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, 3<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6.<ref>[http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/players/overview/atpmc65.html 2011 Wimbledon Results]</ref>

At the [[2011 Legg Mason Tennis Classic|Legg Mason Tennis Classic]] in Washington DC, he reached the finals with victories over [[Ryan Sweeting]], [[Dmitry Tursunov]], [[Janko Tipsarevic]], and [[John Isner]]. He lost to [[Radek Stepanek]] in the final 4<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6. He reached the quarterfinals of both the [[2011 Rogers Cup|Rogers Cup]] and the [[2011 Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati Masters]], where he lost to [[Novak Djokovic]]. At the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], he lost in the second round to [[Juan Carlos Ferrero]] after a hard-fought match 6<U+2013>7, 7<U+2013>5, 7<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6.<ref>{{cite web|title=Enthralling, infuriating case of Gael Monfils|url=http://tennis.si.com/2011/09/01/enthralling-infuriating-case-of-gael-monfils/|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=Sep 01, 2011}}</ref>  Monfils then won his fourth ATP career title in October at the [[2011 If Stockholm Open|Stockholm Open]] by beating [[Jarkko Nieminen]] in the final. It was Nieminen's 11th ATP-level career final, and Monfils' 15th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/10/23/monfils-pulls-out-win-in-stockholm-final|title=Monfils pulls out win in Stockholm final|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=October 23, 2011}}</ref>

===2012===

Monfils began 2012 reaching the final of the [[Qatar Open (tennis)|Qatar Open]]. On his way to the final, he beat [[Rui Machado]], 7<U+2013>5, 6<U+2013>3, [[Benjamin Becker]], 7<U+2013>5, 4<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>5, [[Viktor Troicki]], 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>3, and [[Rafael Nadal]] in straight sets, 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>4.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monfils upsets Nadal to set up all-French Qatar final|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2012/01/06/tennis-men-doha-nadal-idINDEE8050IA20120106|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Jan 6, 2012}}</ref>  In the final, Monfils faced [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]], who had received a walkover after [[Roger Federer]] withdrew from the tournament due to a back problem. Monfils proceeded to lose the final, 5<U+2013>7, 3<U+2013>6. At the Australian Open, Monfils progressed to the third round before bowing out to [[Mikhail Kukushkin]] in five sets. Monfils was suffering from a back injury he received in the previous round. In his next tournament at Montpellier. Monfils reached the final, losing to [[Tom<U+00E1><U+0161> Berdych]] in three sets. This brought his finals record to just 4 titles out of 17 finals.

He reached the third round in Madrid, again losing to Berdych. He has not played on tour since Nice in May due to a knee injury.<ref>{{cite news|title=France's Monfils pulls out of French Open|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/05/24/us-tennis-open-monfils-idUSBRE84N14L20120524|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Olympics-Monfils withdraws from tennis competition|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/07/20/oly-tenn-fra-monfils-adv-idUSL4E8IK4O020120720|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Jul 20, 2012}}</ref>   
The comeback came in Metz indoor in september where he reached the quarterfinal in which he lost to [[Andreas Seppi]] in three sets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tsonga reaches Metz final, Seppi beats Monfils|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/22/us-tennis-france-metz-idUSBRE88L07O20120922|accessdate=8 October 2012|newspaper=Reuters|date=Sep 22, 2012}}</ref> Monfils withdrew from the [[2012 Rakuten Japan Open Tennis Championships|Rakuten Japan Open Tennis Championships]] in October citing pain in his right knee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gael Monfils withdraws from Tokyo|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=8 October 2012|date=Oct 01, 2012}}</ref>

